    <div class="card-body hbInfo">
      <p class="card-text hbText"><em>Haas-Bioroid</em> is the value town corp. They can do a bit of everything
        and they do it for a decent price. What they care about most is efficiency, clicks are king for HB. They have
        a plethora of ways to gain clicks and bioroid ICE, while good value, can be broken if the runner spends
        clicks. If the runner is more efficient than HB, HB loses.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body jintekiInfo d-none">
      <p class="card-text jintekiText"><em>Jinteki</em> is all about manipulation. They're not very good at
        keeping the runner out of their stuff so their main defense is asking the runner if they really want to.
        Plenty of taxing ICE that's a real pain to deal with and traps to go at the end of them to make you regret
        every choice that lead you to that point. If the runner guesses
        right on the shell games or has a way to pay through whatever nonsense Jinteki is trying to pull off, they'll
        get there.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body weylandInfo d-none">
      <p class="card-text weylandText"><em>Weyland</em> is a rich bastard. Getting extravagant piles of cash is
        what Weyland is best at. Then they erect great hulking walls to keep the runner out. If things don't go their
        way they have a tantrum and try to blow the runner up with a pile of meat damage. Things tend to go wrong for
        Weyland when they don't have as much money as they'd like.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body nbnInfo d-none">
      <p class="card-text nbnText">
        <em>NBN</em> loves information. They're great at landing tags and punishing you in a host of different
        ways. They're also great at drawing and filtering cards. To top it off, NBN is amazing at scoring agendas
        out of hand. NBN loses when the runner has a way to slow them down or just straight up overrun them.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
